The paper focuses on modeling and analyzing activity dynamics in collaboration networks, which involves social influence and user incentives. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Social and Information Retrieval (cs.SI) or Social and Information Networks (cs.SOC) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the ramp-up problem and dwindling activity within online collaboration networks, which could fall under the Cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) or Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-categories. Finally, the paper introduces a new metric to assess the activity robustness of collaboration networks, which could also be relevant to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
